Returns the number of elements in the set.

# Examples

```
use std::collections::HashSet;

let mut v = HashSet::new();
assert_eq!(v.len(), 0);
v.insert(1);
assert_eq!(v.len(), 1);
```

An iterator visiting all elements in arbitrary order.
The iterator element type is `&'a T`.

# Examples

```
use std::collections::HashSet;
let mut set = HashSet::new();
set.insert("a");
set.insert("b");

// Will print in an arbitrary order.
for x in set.iter() {
    println!("{x}");
}
```

# Performance

In the current implementation, iterating over set takes O(capacity) time
instead of O(len) because it internally visits empty buckets too.

core::iter::Iterator::all.doc:
Tests if every element of the iterator matches a predicate.

`all()` takes a closure that returns `true` or `false`. It applies
this closure to each element of the iterator, and if they all return
`true`, then so does `all()`. If any of them return `false`, it
returns `false`.

`all()` is short-circuiting; in other words, it will stop processing
as soon as it finds a `false`, given that no matter what else happens,
the result will also be `false`.

An empty iterator returns `true`.

# Examples

Basic usage:

```
let a = [1, 2, 3];

assert!(a.into_iter().all(|x| x > 0));

assert!(!a.into_iter().all(|x| x > 2));
```

Stopping at the first `false`:

```
let a = [1, 2, 3];

let mut iter = a.into_iter();

assert!(!iter.all(|x| x != 2));

// we can still use `iter`, as there are more elements.
assert_eq!(iter.next(), Some(3));
```

